snippet.textDisplay:
I've been saying this for some time now; the young kids coming through are GOOD. Scarily good. Because now they are training hard with not only technique (meaning, they can ALL hit good shots with good shape), but with strategy and tactics.


So many times, I see pro level players hitting discretionary shots up the middle. This does NOTHING to damage the opponent, and gives them time to hit where THEY want. Cross court with good angle and spin will pull a player off court and open up more court for your next strike. And yes, sometimes that gives them a chance to hit a winner. You have to say "too good", and move on. But tennis is a game of statistics, percentages, and forced errors. For every time an opponent goes over the high part of the net to hit a winner down the line, I can almost guarantee they will make errors, because they have been stressed to run out wide. Do this enough in a match, and over time, you will wear down your opponent, and the errors will grow.


That is what so many young players are being taught now, AS WELL as the technique.


They are coming, and players like Yastremska, Gauff, Osaka, Sabalenka, will displace the old guard soon enough, if they haven't already. And yes, I know many of them have lost in the AO. What do you expect? Out of a main draw of 128, 127 will lose. Is this a surprise to anyone?
